SIMPLE: abscond
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Abscond
<hw>Ab*scond"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Absconded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Absconding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>abscondere</ets> to
hide; <ets>ab</ets>, <ets>abs</ets> + <ets>condere</ets> to lay up;
<ets>con</ets> + <ets>d⟦acr⟧re</ets> (only in comp.) to put. Cf.
<er>Do</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hide, withdraw, or be
concealed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The marmot <qex>absconds</qex> all winter.</q>
<rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To depart clandestinely; to steal off and secrete
one's self; -- used especially of persons who withdraw to avoid a legal
process; <as>as, an <ex>absconding</ex> debtor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That very homesickness which, in regular armies, drives so many
recruits to <qex>abscond</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Abscond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Abscond
<hw>Ab*scond"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To hide; to conceal.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Abscondence</ent>⟦br⟧
